217
00:12:40,929 --> 00:12:41,999
Continuous enforcement.

218
00:12:42,089 --> 00:12:47,159
So replace point-in-time decisions with
single signal-driven authorization.

219
00:12:47,659 --> 00:12:48,999
Unified governance.

220
00:12:49,199 --> 00:12:53,929
Human services and agents under
one framework with consistent

221
00:12:53,929 --> 00:12:55,469
policy, audit, and lifecycle.

222
00:12:55,499 --> 00:12:58,429
So lifecycle is very critical
in this process So what are the

223
00:12:58,489 --> 00:13:00,789
common patterns we need to avoid?

224
00:13:01,379 --> 00:13:02,379
So let's look at that.

225
00:13:02,879 --> 00:13:03,659
Rapid fire.

226
00:13:04,159 --> 00:13:07,589
So over-privileged service accounts.

227
00:13:07,599 --> 00:13:10,969
So broad access granted for convenience.

228
00:13:11,349 --> 00:13:12,309
Never scope down.

229
00:13:12,319 --> 00:13:16,429
One token can take down your whole
platform or your en-whole environment.

230
00:13:16,619 --> 00:13:17,549
So that should be avoided.

231
00:13:17,689 --> 00:13:23,109
So over-privileged service account should
be reviewed and it should be scaled down.

232
00:13:23,119 --> 00:13:24,369
The permission should be scaled down.

233
00:13:24,869 --> 00:13:25,839
Credential sprawl.

234
00:13:25,879 --> 00:13:29,709
So keys and tokens hardcoded in code,
config, and environmental variables

235
00:13:29,709 --> 00:13:33,159
ungoverned and in-and invisible.

236
00:13:33,159 --> 00:13:36,389
So it should be governed in a proper
way that we have all the inventory and

237
00:13:36,389 --> 00:13:37,149
it's visible to, to the whole admins.

238
00:13:37,649 --> 00:13:39,049
Implicit agent trust.

239
00:13:39,049 --> 00:13:43,469
So framework passing identity
context without re-authentication.

240
00:13:43,479 --> 00:13:48,259
So a compromised sub-agent
inherits the parent's trust.

241
00:13:48,759 --> 00:13:51,479
And then siloed identity operations.

242
00:13:51,489 --> 00:13:52,169
So what it means?

243
00:13:52,179 --> 00:13:58,319
So humans owned by IT, service
accounts by DevOps, agents by nobody.

244
00:13:59,119 --> 00:14:02,859
So none of these are like zero
days, they are governance gaps.

245
00:14:02,869 --> 00:14:07,539
So it, it is not like somebody is going
to release a a zero-day vulnerability

246
00:14:07,539 --> 00:14:08,979
alert that you have to fix it.

247
00:14:08,979 --> 00:14:14,469
It's a governance gap which has to be
leveled up when AI infrastructure or AI

248
00:14:14,469 --> 00:14:19,339
agent or AI's application is brought into
your environment So those are some of the

249
00:14:19,339 --> 00:14:21,469
common failures which needs to be avoided.

250
00:14:21,969 --> 00:14:23,599
So what are the key takeaways here?

251
00:14:24,079 --> 00:14:27,489
One, elevate IAM to a
infrastructure status.

252
00:14:28,009 --> 00:14:30,969
Same rigor as networking or compute.

253
00:14:30,969 --> 00:14:35,149
So it's not just so you, you-- we
are focusing more on firewall rules

254
00:14:35,149 --> 00:14:38,249
and network bound-boundaries, but
identity is the new perimeter.

255
00:14:38,289 --> 00:14:41,649
So you have to focus on
designing and applying governance

256
00:14:41,649 --> 00:14:44,939
controls on the IAM plane.

257
00:14:45,439 --> 00:14:47,899
Govern non-human identity.

258
00:14:47,919 --> 00:14:52,939
So in most of the organizations
today, there is a governance process

259
00:14:52,939 --> 00:14:54,649
for human identities in fact.

260
00:14:54,649 --> 00:14:58,019
So we have MFA, we have audits,
regulatories which governs it.

261
00:14:58,059 --> 00:15:01,129
But for non-human
identities, it's different.

262
00:15:01,729 --> 00:15:06,899
So inventory and scope them
properly, and then make sure the

263
00:15:06,899 --> 00:15:10,129
least privilege and rotation is
happening for all the credentials.

264
00:15:10,629 --> 00:15:12,849
Architect for continuous verification.

265
00:15:12,879 --> 00:15:14,599
So again, the same point, right?

266
00:15:14,609 --> 00:15:18,899
So for non-human identities, there
should be a continuous verification to

267
00:15:18,929 --> 00:15:24,659
make sure if the service or application
which it was supporting is still active.

268
00:15:25,159 --> 00:15:29,489
The final takeaway is the network
perimeter can't follow your

269
00:15:29,529 --> 00:15:31,809
workloads, but identity can.

270
00:15:32,239 --> 00:15:38,779
So build identity first before
you scale AI, before retrofitting

271
00:15:38,779 --> 00:15:38,819
governance after an incident.

272
00:15:38,819 --> 00:15:44,089
So we should be defining life cycle,
making sure there is governance process

273
00:15:44,399 --> 00:15:49,189
against all the AI identities before
even you bring it into your environment.

274
00:15:49,689 --> 00:15:52,669
And if we are not doing that, the
lessons are going to be expensive.

275
00:15:52,709 --> 00:15:55,119
So we should be careful in this.

276
00:15:55,619 --> 00:15:59,019
So with that I'm closing my slides.

277
